{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is the handoff between request-construction logic and the API client payload. A pure unit test of a formatter could miss wiring bugs where taxonomy is dropped before dispatch. Rejection-gate: System rejected because behavior text is about payload content, not real network/OS/subprocess effects; Agentic/Workflow rejected because correctness does not depend on model judgment.","test_description":"Wire classifier module to a stub transport/client that captures outbound requests; invoke classification with a known taxonomy and assert the sent payload contains the full label set every time.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is local normalization/guard logic: given taxonomy + raw returned label, map out-of-taxonomy values to \"unknown\". No real infra or module wiring is required to expose the failure.","test_description":"Call the normalization/response-mapping function with invalid labels (e.g., \"medical\") and assert output is exactly \"unknown\".","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.8,"Integration":0.17,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the same final label.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Determinism of normalization is a pure function property. No external boundary is needed; failure is in local parsing/canonicalization logic.","test_description":"Run normalization repeatedly on identical raw response fixtures (case/whitespace variants already fixed per fixture) and assert identical final label each run.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On repeated live API calls for the same document and taxonomy, the returned label remains consistent unless the provider response itself changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior explicitly requires repeated live AI API calls and consistency of model-returned labels; mocks would hide model/output variability. Rejection-gate: Workflow rejected because this is repeated single-step classification, not a multi-stage agent pipeline.","test_description":"Execute N real provider calls for the same input over a short window, log raw provider labels, and assert module output is stable whenever raw provider output is unchanged; classify drift as provider-response change vs module inconsistency.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.18,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is policy + request-builder + dispatch gate ordering (enforced before send). A unit test of tokenizer/policy alone can miss wiring/order bugs. Rejection-gate: System rejected because real network is not required; Agentic/Workflow rejected because no dependence on model decision quality.","test_description":"Configure a small budget, run classifier with oversized input through real module wiring and a capturing stub client, then assert either truncation or rejection per policy occurs before any outbound call.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.58,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This depends on real AI provider token accounting on live requests; stubs can force passing values and miss real over-budget behavior caused by provider tokenization/usage reporting. Rejection-gate: Workflow rejected because only one model call path is evaluated, not chained agentic stages.","test_description":"Send representative documents to the real provider via the module, capture provider-reported usage fields, and assert usage <= configured budget for each call.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.07,"System":0.3,"Agentic":0.6,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is orchestration/retry behavior across classifier + API client + retry policy/timer modules. In-process stubs can reproduce 429/rate-limit signals and verify retry path. Rejection-gate: System rejected because behavior text does not require real network timing primitives to expose logic failure; Agentic/Workflow rejected because correctness is retry orchestration, not model-output quality or multi-agent sequencing.","test_description":"Use a stub provider that returns rate-limit error first then success; assert module delays per policy, retries, and returns successful label instead of surfacing the first error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
